WEBVTT

00:07.382 --> 00:09.632
- Previously
on "Resident Alien"...

00:09.676 --> 00:11.426
- If you care even just
a little bit about me,

00:11.470 --> 00:13.760
you need to tell me
what’s really going on.

00:13.805 --> 00:15.215
- It’s fine.
- No.

00:15.265 --> 00:17.475
- Maybe it’s best
if we just leave it at this.

00:17.518 --> 00:18.598
- [sobs]

00:19.811 --> 00:21.401
- I’m not an alien.

00:21.438 --> 00:23.478
The aliens are the ones
who took me.

00:23.524 --> 00:25.194
- You remember.

00:25.234 --> 00:26.744
You’re not supposed
to remember.

00:26.777 --> 00:28.567
- You’re one of them.

00:28.612 --> 00:30.822
- What is this?
- Oh, that was a hoax

00:30.864 --> 00:32.284
started by the mayor’s son.

00:32.324 --> 00:34.284
I already questioned him.
It was nothing.

00:34.326 --> 00:36.536
Unless it means something
to you.

00:39.957 --> 00:42.917
[somber music]

00:42.960 --> 00:46.630
♪ ♪

00:46.672 --> 00:48.302
[both chuckle]

00:48.340 --> 00:50.050
- Wow.

00:50.092 --> 00:52.302
You went all out.

00:52.344 --> 00:54.144
I can’t believe you made this.

00:54.179 --> 00:58.929
- Well, it is a special day.

00:58.976 --> 01:02.096
He or she
would have been two today.

01:02.145 --> 01:06.355
- Honey, listen.

01:06.400 --> 01:09.900
Maybe it’s time we try again,
hmm?

01:09.945 --> 01:11.655
- Honey...

01:11.697 --> 01:13.617
I love you.

01:13.657 --> 01:15.487
I just--
- I know.

01:16.868 --> 01:19.118
It’s just too soon.

01:19.162 --> 01:21.502
- Okay.

01:21.540 --> 01:22.960
But just...

01:23.000 --> 01:25.670
say the word when you’re ready,

01:25.711 --> 01:29.511
and I promise
to bring my A game.

01:29.548 --> 01:30.718
- [chuckles]

01:30.757 --> 01:33.377
You always bring your A game.
- Mm.

01:33.427 --> 01:35.847
- Sometimes your B and C game.
- [laughs]

01:35.887 --> 01:38.517
- [laughs]

01:38.557 --> 01:39.767
- You, uh...
[electricity warbles]

01:39.808 --> 01:42.638
- Think it’s okay
if we sing "Happy Birth"--

01:42.686 --> 01:46.606
[ominous music]

01:46.648 --> 01:48.358
- [screams]

01:48.400 --> 01:49.690
- What the hell happened?

01:49.735 --> 01:51.865
- They took me again.

01:51.903 --> 01:54.203
I saw our baby.

01:54.239 --> 01:56.199
It’s a boy.

01:56.241 --> 01:58.121
[sobs] It’s a boy!

01:59.411 --> 02:02.081
[screams]

02:02.122 --> 02:04.502
[sobbing]

02:05.459 --> 02:08.459
[Brown Bird’s "Bilgewater"]

02:08.503 --> 02:11.593
[laid-back acoustic strumming]

02:11.632 --> 02:15.512
♪ ♪

02:16.637 --> 02:18.507
[banging at door]

02:18.555 --> 02:20.715
- Open up.

02:20.766 --> 02:23.176
Honey, let me in!

02:23.226 --> 02:25.226
- Honey, what are you doing?

02:25.270 --> 02:27.230
Oh, my gosh.
Come--come inside.

02:27.272 --> 02:28.902
- W-what am I doing down here?

02:28.940 --> 02:31.780
- I...

02:31.818 --> 02:32.898
You tell me.

02:32.944 --> 02:35.204
I--you were just yelling

02:35.238 --> 02:37.488
and--and knocking
and asking me to let you in.

02:37.532 --> 02:39.782
You--your hands are ice cold.

02:39.826 --> 02:41.036
- Huh.

02:41.078 --> 02:43.198
- Hey, come on.
I’ll make you some tea.

02:45.582 --> 02:48.002
- Yeah, I think
I was sleepwalking.

02:48.043 --> 02:49.923
- Since when do you sleepwalk?

02:49.961 --> 02:52.011
- [sighs] Well, I...

02:52.047 --> 02:54.377
did it a couple times as a kid.

02:54.424 --> 02:57.764
Yeah, I’d sleepwalk
and always have the same dream.

02:58.929 --> 03:00.349
- What was the dream?

03:00.389 --> 03:04.429
- Uh, well, I’m in bed
with a broken leg,

03:04.476 --> 03:07.936
and my whole family
is standing over me.

03:07.979 --> 03:10.979
You know, my mom, dad,
aunts, uncles.

03:11.024 --> 03:12.284
Yeah, it’s so weird.

03:12.317 --> 03:15.067
I keep trying to ask
for their help,

03:15.112 --> 03:17.612
but nothing comes out
of my mouth.

03:17.656 --> 03:18.526
- Hmm.

03:18.573 --> 03:21.993
- And they just...stand there

03:22.035 --> 03:23.785
looking at me...

03:23.829 --> 03:26.789
not doing anything.

03:26.832 --> 03:28.082
- Hmm.

03:28.125 --> 03:29.885
Why are you having
this nightmare now

03:29.918 --> 03:31.418
after all these years?

03:32.462 --> 03:34.712
- Maybe it’s those new sheets
you got.

03:34.756 --> 03:36.296
- Uh, no.

03:36.341 --> 03:37.971
Those are Egyptian cotton.

03:38.009 --> 03:40.639
They were, like, $200,

03:40.679 --> 03:42.759
- Great, now I’m gonna
have nightmares

03:42.806 --> 03:44.886
about how much you spent
on sheets.

03:49.813 --> 03:52.113
- All right. Here we go.

03:52.149 --> 03:54.109
Number 17
on the Joe’s Diner menu,

03:54.151 --> 03:56.281
Rocky Mountain eggs over easy.

03:56.319 --> 03:57.699
Maybe. Who knows?

03:57.738 --> 03:59.108
You’ll have to see
when you get inside the egg.

03:59.156 --> 04:00.526
Everybody loves a mystery.

04:00.574 --> 04:02.034
- Doesn’t matter
as long as someone else

04:02.075 --> 04:03.115
is doing the cooking.

04:03.160 --> 04:04.790
- Good morning.

04:04.828 --> 04:06.328
Mmm.
- Hello.

04:06.371 --> 04:08.001
- Welcome to D’arcy’s Diner.

04:08.039 --> 04:10.789
I made you your favorite,
blueberry pancakes.

04:10.834 --> 04:13.004
- Oh, that...

04:13.044 --> 04:14.134
is your favorite.

04:14.171 --> 04:15.841
- Yeah, well,
I’m your favorite,

04:15.881 --> 04:18.591
so whatever is in my stomach
is your favorite.

04:18.633 --> 04:19.883
- Hmm.

04:19.926 --> 04:21.756
Thank you, but I will
just have coffee today.

04:21.803 --> 04:23.143
And, you know, you don’t have
to cook breakfast

04:23.180 --> 04:24.350
for us every day.

04:24.389 --> 04:25.809
- Speak for yourself.

04:25.849 --> 04:27.019
- Well, it’s the least
I could do.

04:27.058 --> 04:28.518
You know, you’ve been
letting me stay here

04:28.560 --> 04:30.600
the last few days, and...

04:30.645 --> 04:33.855
getting over the pain pills
was hard, you know?

04:33.899 --> 04:36.029
But thanks to you, I feel like
I’m over the hump.

04:36.067 --> 04:38.027
- Okay. Great.

04:38.069 --> 04:39.859
Okay, so you’re gonna
go back to work today.

04:39.905 --> 04:41.495
- Oh. Ugh.

04:41.531 --> 04:43.701
I mean, you know,
it’s a big hump.

04:43.742 --> 04:45.542
- Oh.
- You know, my recovery group

04:45.577 --> 04:48.497
meets for three hours a day.

04:48.538 --> 04:50.868
And then after that, it’s like,
where’s the day gone?

04:50.916 --> 04:53.786
You know? Love to. Can’t.

04:53.835 --> 04:55.295
So...
- Hmm.

04:55.337 --> 04:56.417
- I think I’m gonna do
some laundry

04:56.463 --> 04:57.883
and then start
on tonight’s lasagna.

04:57.923 --> 04:59.883
- Uh-huh.
- Hmm.

04:59.925 --> 05:01.385
- Hey, do you wanna go

05:01.426 --> 05:03.426
to the record store later,
maybe?

05:03.470 --> 05:05.180
Get some new vinyl? New stuff?

05:05.222 --> 05:06.512
Think about it.

05:08.642 --> 05:09.852
- She doesn’t seem very eager

05:09.893 --> 05:11.733
to go back to her life,
does she?

05:11.770 --> 05:13.690
- Well, I’m sure
she will eventually.

05:13.730 --> 05:14.730
[chuckles]
- I don’t know.

05:14.773 --> 05:16.823
You know, going back to work,

05:16.858 --> 05:19.028
at least she’s gonna
face the world, right?

05:19.069 --> 05:21.199
How fulfilling could it be
cooking all day?

05:21.238 --> 05:22.528
- I don’t know.

05:22.572 --> 05:24.872
I mean, why don’t you ask
the roof over your head?

05:26.243 --> 05:27.913
Oh, okay, I’m sorry.

05:27.953 --> 05:29.413
I love this roof.

05:29.454 --> 05:31.834
Okay? But so does she.

05:31.873 --> 05:33.123
Like, a lot.

05:33.166 --> 05:34.916
So maybe you could give her
a nudge, you know?

05:34.960 --> 05:36.460
I’m her best friend.
It’s delicate.

05:36.503 --> 05:37.803
But I’ll need
to be there for her

05:37.838 --> 05:40.208
when my mean old dad
kicks her out.

05:40.257 --> 05:41.507
Please?

05:41.550 --> 05:43.510
- Fine.
- Okay.

05:43.552 --> 05:45.392
- She’ll be gone
by the time you get home.

05:45.428 --> 05:47.558
- Thank you.
- I’ll talk to her.

05:47.597 --> 05:49.427
Right after she makes
the lasagna.

05:49.474 --> 05:50.934
- [laughs]

05:50.976 --> 05:53.306
You’re enjoying this
way too much.

05:53.353 --> 05:56.813
- [muffled]

05:56.857 --> 05:59.107
- I discovered humans
are bound together.

05:59.150 --> 06:01.690
They are committed
to each other through family,

06:01.736 --> 06:04.486
work, a common cause.

06:04.531 --> 06:06.241
I came to Earth
because I was committed

06:06.283 --> 06:07.833
to saving the planet.

06:07.868 --> 06:08.988
Ah! Ahh-ahh!

06:09.035 --> 06:10.495
And I will stop anybody

06:10.537 --> 06:11.747
who gets in my way...
[electricity buzzing]

06:11.788 --> 06:13.618
and take their cool things.

06:13.665 --> 06:15.635
[laughs]

06:15.667 --> 06:17.457
[knocks at door]
- Harry? Are you in there?

06:17.502 --> 06:19.382
[clattering]

06:19.421 --> 06:22.971
[sighs]

06:23.008 --> 06:24.468
You’re not answering
your phone.

06:24.509 --> 06:27.099
- Did you call me to tell me
to come in to work?

06:27.137 --> 06:28.347
- Yes.

06:28.388 --> 06:30.308
- That is why
I did not answer it.

06:30.348 --> 06:31.718
- Well, if you would have
answered it,

06:31.766 --> 06:33.766
you would know
that I ran into Liv,

06:33.810 --> 06:37.980
and she said the alien tracker
has left town.

06:38.023 --> 06:39.273
- Oh!

06:39.316 --> 06:40.436
- So you can come out
of hiding.

06:40.483 --> 06:41.653
And we have a backlog,

06:41.693 --> 06:43.493
so I could really use you
at the clinic.

06:43.528 --> 06:46.528
- Oh, I cannot come in
to work today

06:46.573 --> 06:50.163
’cause I’m sick...with a fever.

06:50.201 --> 06:51.371
- Oh?

06:52.329 --> 06:54.499
- Y--ow!

06:54.539 --> 06:56.169
- You don’t have a fever.

06:56.207 --> 06:58.287
- I mean the gout.

06:58.335 --> 07:00.295
I’ve been eating organ meats...

07:00.337 --> 07:03.337
on my pizza.

07:03.381 --> 07:05.131
- Your baby is sleeping.

07:06.217 --> 07:07.507
- What was that?

07:07.552 --> 07:08.762
- That was me.

07:08.803 --> 07:10.853
I’m practicing ventriloquism.

07:10.889 --> 07:12.309
[high-pitched voice]
Your baby is sleeping.

07:12.349 --> 07:13.809
I’m very good at it.

07:13.850 --> 07:16.690
Goodbye.

07:16.728 --> 07:18.768
- Your baby is turning.

07:18.813 --> 07:20.443
- [high-pitched voice]
The baby is turning.

07:20.482 --> 07:22.822
Into what? [laughs]

07:22.859 --> 07:25.189
- Harry.
[device beeps]

07:25.236 --> 07:27.196
- [muffled]

07:27.238 --> 07:28.488
- What did you do?

07:28.531 --> 07:30.321
- [muffled]

07:30.367 --> 07:31.697
- Oh!

07:31.743 --> 07:33.333
How did that get
into my bunker?

07:33.370 --> 07:35.580
I need to call
an exterminator.

07:37.248 --> 07:38.788
[grumbles]

07:44.673 --> 07:47.183
- Oh, God. I am so sorry.

07:47.217 --> 07:50.047
Harry can be
a little serial killer-y.

07:50.095 --> 07:51.855
- [groans]

07:51.888 --> 07:54.218
- What are you thinking?
You’re kidnapping people now?

07:54.265 --> 07:56.095
- I had to.
He tried to electrocute me

07:56.142 --> 07:58.392
with his cooking stick
for no reason.

07:58.436 --> 08:00.646
- You ripped an implant
out of my neck.

08:00.689 --> 08:01.899
I almost bled to death.

08:01.940 --> 08:04.110
- I did not rip.

08:04.150 --> 08:06.360
I cut with the scalpel.

08:06.403 --> 08:08.613
Oh! That did not heal well.

08:08.655 --> 08:10.705
You should have put vitamin E
on it.

08:10.740 --> 08:13.950
- That chip was my only
connection with my son.

08:13.994 --> 08:17.254
Now I may never find him again
thanks to this monster.

08:17.288 --> 08:20.368
- This is why I wrapped a rag
around his mouth.

08:20.417 --> 08:23.087
- Stop.
W-what happened to your son?

08:23.128 --> 08:24.458
- [sighs]

08:24.504 --> 08:27.384
Our baby was abducted
out of my wife’s womb

08:27.424 --> 08:28.764
when she was eight months
pregnant.

08:28.800 --> 08:30.050
- Unlikely.

08:30.093 --> 08:32.683
- We were on a bus,
and the next thing I knew,

08:32.721 --> 08:35.181
she was screaming
and the baby was gone.

08:35.223 --> 08:37.433
- That must have been awful.

08:37.475 --> 08:39.185
- It was.

08:39.227 --> 08:43.107
They implanted me
with a tracking chip,

08:43.148 --> 08:45.818
and over the years
they would take one

08:45.859 --> 08:47.779
or both of us up to see him,

08:47.819 --> 08:51.449
but they stopped that
after he took my chip.

08:52.782 --> 08:54.452
- I am so sorry.

08:54.492 --> 08:56.952
Harry’s sorry too.
Aren’t you, Harry?

08:56.995 --> 08:58.965
- No.

08:58.997 --> 09:00.957
That thing looks ugly.
- Harry.

09:00.999 --> 09:02.459
- Do you put sunscreen on it?

09:02.500 --> 09:03.960
It’s the size of a scallop.

09:04.002 --> 09:05.292
- I’m sorry.
- You know what?

09:05.336 --> 09:06.626
- I’m so sorry.
- It’s too late.

09:06.671 --> 09:08.301
- Harry.

09:08.339 --> 09:12.639
- Here, in my pocket
is my only picture of my son.

09:14.888 --> 09:17.008
[gentle piano music]

09:17.057 --> 09:18.557
- Oh.

09:18.600 --> 09:20.640
- Yeah.

09:20.685 --> 09:22.135
Do you have kids?

09:22.187 --> 09:24.437
- Yeah. I have a daughter.

09:25.523 --> 09:26.653
- I just keep thinking,

09:26.691 --> 09:29.991
what could I have done
differently?

09:30.028 --> 09:31.358
- I know how you feel.

09:31.404 --> 09:33.824
- Why are you talking
like you are friends now?

09:33.865 --> 09:34.995
He is an enemy.

09:35.033 --> 09:36.333
He is not our friend.

09:36.367 --> 09:38.487
The only reason
I have kept him alive

09:38.536 --> 09:41.496
is because I need to learn more
about the Greys.

09:41.539 --> 09:45.209
And to torture him a little.

09:45.251 --> 09:47.751
I’m not touching you.

09:47.796 --> 09:49.006
Oh!

09:49.047 --> 09:50.507
I’m not touching you.

09:50.548 --> 09:52.218
- You should be
helping each other,

09:52.258 --> 09:54.048
not trying to kill one another.

09:54.094 --> 09:58.354
- I would be willing to do that
if you will just untie me.

09:58.389 --> 10:02.439
- Ha-ha! Ha-ha-ha-ha!

10:02.477 --> 10:03.847
What are you doing?

10:03.895 --> 10:05.235
He wants to kill me.

10:05.271 --> 10:07.361
- I swear on my son,

10:07.398 --> 10:10.688
I won’t hurt you
if you don’t hurt me.

10:10.735 --> 10:11.565
- Whatever.

10:11.611 --> 10:14.451
I’ll swear at your son too.

10:14.489 --> 10:16.279
There is no point
in me resisting.

10:16.324 --> 10:18.704
Asta always does
the right thing.

10:18.743 --> 10:20.753
It is her most annoying trait.

10:20.787 --> 10:23.707
That and she never lets me
kill anyone.

10:23.748 --> 10:26.628
- [snoring]

10:30.046 --> 10:31.836
Oh!

10:31.881 --> 10:33.721
- What is going on?

10:33.758 --> 10:35.838
I mean, I’ve never seen you
sleep on the job before.

10:35.885 --> 10:38.505
I mean, maybe metaphorically,
but never literally.

10:38.555 --> 10:40.065
- Look, I--I didn’t get
a lot of sleep

10:40.098 --> 10:41.848
last night, okay?
- Okay, look here,

10:41.891 --> 10:43.481
this is a place
of business, all right?

10:43.518 --> 10:46.398
So I don’t wanna here nothing
about your sexual Etch-A-Sketch

10:46.437 --> 10:49.227
nipple play with your wife,
all right?

10:49.274 --> 10:50.734
- I agree. I don’t ever wanna

10:50.775 --> 10:52.275
hear that spoken out loud
either.

10:52.318 --> 10:53.488
- You know what?
I’ma tell you something.

10:53.528 --> 10:54.698
You need to write this down.

10:56.739 --> 10:57.819
Ahh.

11:00.827 --> 11:02.327
Sleep...

11:02.370 --> 11:05.410
is a state of mind.

11:05.456 --> 11:06.706
You’re welcome.

11:06.749 --> 11:08.499
- Yeah, I think
that’s a known thing.

11:08.543 --> 11:10.343
Might even be
in the definition.

11:12.505 --> 11:14.375
- Here you go.
- Thanks, Debra.

11:14.424 --> 11:15.884
- Good morning, Sheriff.

11:15.925 --> 11:16.795
- Good morning, Debra.

11:19.804 --> 11:21.104
Did you see that?

11:21.139 --> 11:22.429
- What?

11:24.142 --> 11:26.102
- Debra’s, like, the nicest
person in the office,

11:26.144 --> 11:27.314
but do I get a, "Hi, Ben"?

11:27.353 --> 11:28.653
No. Just, "Here you go."

11:28.688 --> 11:30.438
No, she hates me.
- What?

11:30.481 --> 11:32.321
That woman hates no one
and no thing.

11:32.358 --> 11:35.108
She cried for two days when
that big plant out there died.

11:35.153 --> 11:37.953
Look, this whole lack of sleep
has got you paranoid.

11:37.989 --> 11:39.739
- No, don’t you see
what’s going on here?

11:39.782 --> 11:42.372
Debra is one
of the anti-resorters.

11:42.410 --> 11:43.950
She has it in for me.

11:45.955 --> 11:47.915
Yup. See? Lukewarm.

11:47.957 --> 11:50.577
She probably blew on it
all the way over here.

11:50.627 --> 11:52.287
- Well, that’s actually hot.
That’s--

11:52.337 --> 11:53.957
[slurps]

11:54.005 --> 11:56.135
That’s a good cup
of coffee right there.

11:56.174 --> 11:57.514
- Well, not anymore.

12:01.012 --> 12:02.222
- The steak is enough.

12:02.263 --> 12:05.103
I don’t know why you need a--
a dumb onion.

12:05.141 --> 12:06.771
- Because I’m starving.

12:06.809 --> 12:09.149
All you fed me for three days
is gruel.

12:09.187 --> 12:12.107
- It was
unflavored instant oatmeal.

12:12.148 --> 12:14.778
A-and it’s heart-healthy.

12:14.817 --> 12:15.987
[sniffs]

12:16.027 --> 12:17.147
You’re welcome.

12:17.195 --> 12:18.785
- If you sharpen the knife,

12:18.821 --> 12:20.451
the onion will
make you cry less.

12:20.490 --> 12:22.620
- I know how to chop an onion.

12:22.659 --> 12:26.329
I’m only crying because...

12:26.371 --> 12:28.411
I saw a video this morning
of a dog,

12:28.456 --> 12:30.536
uh, playing with a bird.

12:30.583 --> 12:32.003
- Yeah, I saw that.

12:32.043 --> 12:33.173
It’s fake.

12:33.211 --> 12:35.051
- It was not fake.

12:35.088 --> 12:37.548
[sniffs]

12:37.590 --> 12:38.800
It was beautiful.

12:38.841 --> 12:40.591
- Don’t use your hand--
- Ahh!

12:40.635 --> 12:42.185
I got onion in my eye.

12:42.220 --> 12:43.600
- Mm.
- Son of a bitch!

12:43.638 --> 12:44.968
- I’ll take it from here.

12:45.014 --> 12:47.774
- You take it from here.

12:47.809 --> 12:51.809
- Are you sure your intel
on the Greys is accurate?

12:51.854 --> 12:53.694
- I am sure.

12:53.731 --> 12:57.031
It was implanted
in an alien baby.

12:57.068 --> 12:59.068
The offspring was mine.

12:59.112 --> 13:02.782
But I only got half the message
before the thing ran off,

13:02.824 --> 13:04.834
and then the government
stole it.

13:06.244 --> 13:08.664
- You sound more upset
about the message

13:08.705 --> 13:10.215
than about losing your child.

13:10.248 --> 13:12.788
- It was an important message.

13:12.834 --> 13:15.004
- Well, but it’s your baby.

13:15.044 --> 13:16.464
It’s a part of you.

13:16.504 --> 13:18.674
Caring for it is instinctual.

13:18.715 --> 13:21.225
At least your baby
is being held

13:21.259 --> 13:23.139
at a military base.

13:23.177 --> 13:24.887
Who knows where mine is by now?

13:24.929 --> 13:27.679
- A military base?
What military base?

13:28.474 --> 13:30.064
- There’s a secret base
in Wyoming,

13:30.101 --> 13:33.651
possibly not even funded
by our government.

13:33.688 --> 13:35.728
It’s where I suspect
they keep alien specimens

13:35.773 --> 13:38.653
and probably all their
information on the Greys.

13:38.693 --> 13:43.283
If they took your alien baby,
that’s where it would be.

13:43.323 --> 13:45.533
- How do I get to this base?

13:45.575 --> 13:47.995
- Forget about it.
It’s like Fort Knox.

13:48.036 --> 13:51.156
A friend on the inside
gave me some schematics,

13:51.205 --> 13:53.575
and then he was killed for it.

13:53.624 --> 13:56.594
I even tried to contact
this General McCallister,

13:56.627 --> 13:58.417
who’s supposed to be
in charge there.

13:58.463 --> 13:59.763
That was a mistake.

13:59.797 --> 14:01.967
They were all over me
after that.

14:02.008 --> 14:04.258
I had to go underground
to get away from them.

14:04.302 --> 14:06.262
- Maybe they will let you in

14:06.304 --> 14:08.434
if you have something
they want.

14:08.473 --> 14:11.273
[suspenseful music]

14:11.309 --> 14:18.229
♪ ♪

14:18.274 --> 14:19.734
- Harry.

14:23.237 --> 14:24.407
Peter?

14:29.827 --> 14:32.287
- "Dear Asta,
if you are reading this,

14:32.330 --> 14:34.290
"you are already in my house.

14:34.332 --> 14:38.132
"Me and Pete are going
to break into a military base.

14:38.169 --> 14:40.709
"If we do not come back,
we are dead.

14:40.755 --> 14:43.015
"But do not worry,
that means you will soon

14:43.049 --> 14:44.259
"be dead too.

14:44.300 --> 14:48.100
"You can watch my TV
until that happens.

14:48.137 --> 14:51.557
Stay sweet. Harry."

14:51.599 --> 14:53.229
[tense music]

14:58.940 --> 15:01.530
- So, Detective Torres,
she graduated top of her class

15:01.567 --> 15:03.487
with a degree in criminal
justice from St. John’s.

15:03.528 --> 15:05.318
So obviously she’s smart,
right?

15:05.363 --> 15:06.613
That goes in the pro column.

15:06.656 --> 15:08.026
- Yeah, I don’t think doing
a background check

15:08.074 --> 15:09.494
on someone you like
is a good way

15:09.534 --> 15:10.744
to start a romance.

15:10.785 --> 15:12.375
I never did a background check
on John.

15:12.412 --> 15:14.372
- Oh, that’s okay. I ran him.
He’s clean.

15:14.414 --> 15:15.664
You on the other hand,

15:15.706 --> 15:17.536
you got a C-minus
in social studies.

15:17.583 --> 15:19.043
- Mr. Miller had it in for me.

15:19.085 --> 15:21.255
He said I asked
too many questions.

15:21.295 --> 15:25.005
I mean, do you think I ask
too many questions?

15:25.049 --> 15:26.509
Oh, wow.

15:27.385 --> 15:29.645
- Okay, how about this?
Her blood type is O negative.

15:29.679 --> 15:31.099
Is that a pro or a con?

15:31.139 --> 15:33.769
O negative is universal doner.

15:33.808 --> 15:37.438
They can save a lot of lives,
so pro.

15:37.478 --> 15:38.598
- See, I don’t know about that.

15:38.646 --> 15:39.896
- Why is that, sir?

15:39.939 --> 15:41.399
- I mean, think about it.

15:41.441 --> 15:44.941
People who save a lot of lives,
they give a lot of blood.

15:44.986 --> 15:46.236
But every time they do it,

15:46.279 --> 15:47.659
they get juice and cookies,
right?

15:47.697 --> 15:49.407
Now, what happens if I wanna go
on a picnic, right,

15:49.449 --> 15:50.659
and she just gave blood?

15:50.700 --> 15:51.780
She ain’t gonna have
no appetite

15:51.826 --> 15:53.156
for my lemonade
and snickerdoodles.

15:53.202 --> 15:54.792
I’ll probably have to wait
a week.

15:54.829 --> 15:57.159
Hell, and the ants too.
Now nobody’s happy.

15:57.206 --> 15:59.746
- I don’t know what to say
except that’s just stupid.

15:59.792 --> 16:01.172
- Wow.

16:01.210 --> 16:03.590
How is it possible that
something so negative

16:03.629 --> 16:05.129
can come out of the same face

16:05.173 --> 16:07.553
that makes such beautiful
mouth trumpet sounds?

16:07.592 --> 16:08.762
Huh?
- [sighs]

16:08.801 --> 16:10.141
I’m sorry, sir.

16:10.178 --> 16:12.758
I’m just worried about Peter.

16:12.805 --> 16:14.425
I went on his website

16:14.474 --> 16:17.064
and noticed that he hadn’t
posted anything recently,

16:17.101 --> 16:19.981
and he always posts something,
even if it’s just

16:20.021 --> 16:24.481
to say hi to his fans and
announce the month’s birthdays.

16:24.525 --> 16:27.695
- Man, mine was coming up soon.

16:27.737 --> 16:30.737
[imitates sad trombone noise]

16:30.781 --> 16:33.201
- Aww, I’m sure he’s fine,
Deputy.

16:33.242 --> 16:36.202
- What if Peter did try
to confront an alien

16:36.245 --> 16:39.075
and the alien ended up
taking him captive?

16:39.123 --> 16:40.833
Or worse.
- Okay, now, you might have got

16:40.875 --> 16:42.175
a C-minus in social studies,

16:42.210 --> 16:45.000
but you probably got an A
in conspiracy theories.

16:45.046 --> 16:46.706
- It’s not an actual course.

16:46.756 --> 16:48.466
- How about this one?
She likes rabbits.

16:48.508 --> 16:50.298
Now, see, that’s definitely
a con to me,

16:50.343 --> 16:51.593
’cause I can’t be competing
against something

16:51.636 --> 16:53.006
so furry and cute, right?

16:53.054 --> 16:54.974
And I definitely don’t
shit pellets.

16:55.014 --> 16:58.684
- No. Have you been listening
to me at all?

16:58.726 --> 16:59.846
- What?

16:59.894 --> 17:01.274
- Exactly.

17:06.609 --> 17:07.899
[door closes]

17:07.944 --> 17:09.904
- Hey. How was your day?

17:09.946 --> 17:11.356
- Not great.

17:11.405 --> 17:13.905
I just went to Harry’s
and found this.

17:15.368 --> 17:16.698
I’m worried.

17:16.744 --> 17:19.374
"If we do not come back,
we are dead."

17:19.413 --> 17:20.873
What the hell is that supposed
to mean?

17:20.915 --> 17:22.335
- Well, I don’t think
the problem

17:22.375 --> 17:23.635
with the note is clarity.

17:23.668 --> 17:25.668
- Dan, let’s go.

17:25.711 --> 17:27.001
- She’s still here?

17:27.046 --> 17:28.376
I thought you were supposed
to talk to her.

17:28.422 --> 17:29.342
- I did.

17:29.382 --> 17:31.132
She left
and got her PlayStation

17:31.175 --> 17:34.425
and came back.
- Oh, okay.

17:34.470 --> 17:36.060
- Okay, all set.
Dan, come on. Let’s go.

17:36.097 --> 17:37.467
The Night Monster’s coming.

17:37.515 --> 17:39.435
- Gotta go. The Night Monster.

17:39.475 --> 17:42.685
- Dad.

17:42.728 --> 17:43.938
Okay.

17:45.189 --> 17:47.649
- Where are my Moggles?

17:47.692 --> 17:49.902
Oh, grr.
Now the Beefalo are mad.

17:49.944 --> 17:51.204
- Use your Ham Bat.
[knocks on door]

17:51.237 --> 17:53.697
- Oh, that must be baby-skank
with the snacks.

17:53.739 --> 17:55.319
- You invited Judy?

17:55.366 --> 17:56.576
- Well, you don’t have to
let her in.

17:56.617 --> 17:57.577
You can just take
the snacks.

17:57.618 --> 17:58.738
- We need chips.
- We need sanity.

17:58.786 --> 18:00.116
We’re down to 15%.

18:00.162 --> 18:02.332
- Hey, Judy.
- Hey, Asta!

18:02.373 --> 18:04.463
- Oh.
- Thank you so much

18:04.500 --> 18:06.590
for taking care of our girl.
- Sure.

18:06.627 --> 18:08.917
- I got it from here.

18:08.963 --> 18:13.513
Best friend in the house
with snacks.

18:13.551 --> 18:14.511
- Judy.
- I got you.

18:14.552 --> 18:16.142
Okay, so tonight, D’arcy...

18:16.178 --> 18:17.928
- Judy.
- I got my place tricked out

18:17.972 --> 18:19.682
for you, okay?

18:19.724 --> 18:21.354
I wiped down my comforter.

18:21.392 --> 18:22.432
I--I--

18:22.476 --> 18:25.346
I fixed my "Goonies" tape.
Remember?

18:25.396 --> 18:27.356
And I’ve had, like,
all your favorite candy

18:27.398 --> 18:29.648
out on the counter for, like,
give, take three days

18:29.692 --> 18:32.992
just in case you were to,
you know, have come by sooner.

18:33.988 --> 18:36.318
- Right, but I’m not staying
with you.

18:37.992 --> 18:40.912
- I know. I know that.

18:40.953 --> 18:43.543
That is a better plan
that I stay here.

18:43.581 --> 18:45.501
I totally get it now.

18:45.541 --> 18:48.671
’Cause I weirdly do have a lot
of mice all of a sudden.

18:48.711 --> 18:50.251
- Do you?
- Mm-hmm.

18:50.296 --> 18:51.586
- Huh.

18:51.631 --> 18:53.631
- I’ve made friends with one.

18:53.674 --> 18:55.224
He’s very short.

18:55.259 --> 18:57.259
And I call him...
Bernard.

18:57.303 --> 18:59.263
Like British people say,
"Bernard."

18:59.305 --> 19:01.775
I’m like, "Bernard,
is there more cheese?"

19:01.807 --> 19:03.677
And he’s like,
"No. It’s all mine,"

19:03.726 --> 19:06.346
which is so cute.

19:06.395 --> 19:08.895
[Werepig growls]
- What is this?

19:08.939 --> 19:11.899
[tense music]

19:11.942 --> 19:18.412
♪ ♪

19:18.449 --> 19:21.289
- Sorry, you can’t be here.
This is a restricted area.

19:21.327 --> 19:23.577
- I have a delivery
for General McCallister.

19:23.621 --> 19:25.371
- There’s no one here
by that name.

19:26.791 --> 19:27.831
- You sure about that?

19:27.875 --> 19:33.835
♪ ♪

19:33.881 --> 19:35.511
May I show you something?

19:35.549 --> 19:38.509
♪ ♪

19:38.552 --> 19:39.722
- Jesus Christ.

19:39.762 --> 19:41.602
♪ ♪

19:41.639 --> 19:43.559
- Get me the general.

19:43.599 --> 19:46.059
- [growls]

19:47.061 --> 19:49.731
- Where did you find...this?

19:49.772 --> 19:51.612
- Not out here.

19:51.649 --> 19:53.439
Let’s talk inside.

19:53.484 --> 19:54.904
- I run this base.

19:54.944 --> 19:56.614
You don’t get
to dictate anything.

19:56.654 --> 19:58.364
- Raa!

19:58.406 --> 20:00.196
[growls]

20:00.241 --> 20:02.161
- Well, I am the one
with the alien,

20:02.201 --> 20:05.451
so I will dictate
whatever I want to dictate.

20:05.496 --> 20:09.536
♪ ♪

20:09.583 --> 20:11.633
- You have 20 minutes.

20:11.669 --> 20:12.959
Make it count.

20:13.003 --> 20:20.093
♪ ♪

20:21.011 --> 20:22.051
- [laughs]

20:22.096 --> 20:23.256
- [mouths words]

20:28.561 --> 20:31.271
[tense music]

20:31.313 --> 20:38.403
♪ ♪

20:44.869 --> 20:47.249
- You have about eight minutes
left.

20:48.581 --> 20:51.291
- My sources tell me
this is where you keep

20:51.333 --> 20:53.883
information on alien activity.

20:53.919 --> 20:55.459
I want it.

20:55.504 --> 20:58.304
- Maybe you should stop
listening to rumors from loons

20:58.340 --> 21:00.340
wearing antenna headbands

21:00.384 --> 21:03.644
at your ridiculous
little conventions.

21:03.679 --> 21:05.679
- You seem to know
a lot about me.

21:05.723 --> 21:08.233
- I like to know
who the threats are.

21:08.267 --> 21:09.387
- I’m not a threat.

21:09.435 --> 21:12.355
[alarm blaring]

21:12.396 --> 21:15.356
[tense music]

21:15.399 --> 21:16.859
♪ ♪

21:16.901 --> 21:20.531
- [shouts indistinctly]

21:20.571 --> 21:22.161
[grunts]

21:22.198 --> 21:23.158
- [grunts]

21:23.199 --> 21:27.039
[both grunting]

21:27.077 --> 21:29.197
[suspenseful music]

21:29.246 --> 21:31.366
- So this is it.

21:31.415 --> 21:33.535
You planned this all along.

21:33.584 --> 21:34.964
What are you doing,

21:35.002 --> 21:37.212
working with that thing
you brought with you?

21:37.254 --> 21:39.214
- Now you’re being ridiculous.

21:39.256 --> 21:41.426
Maybe I’m just quick
on my feet.

21:41.467 --> 21:43.337
I would never work
with an alien.

21:43.385 --> 21:44.885
[alarm blaring]

21:44.929 --> 21:47.759
- [laughs]

21:47.807 --> 21:52.557
- Here’s to sending
those resort bastards

21:52.603 --> 21:54.103
on a getaway of their own.

21:54.146 --> 21:55.646
- Let’s not get too excited
yet.

21:55.689 --> 21:57.819
It’s just a TRO.
We’ve got a long way to go.

21:57.858 --> 21:59.358
- I know, but if I’m drinking
before dinner

21:59.401 --> 22:00.781
and we tie it to work,

22:00.820 --> 22:02.530
it just feels
more professional.

22:02.571 --> 22:03.991
- Okay, yeah.
I can drink to that.

22:04.031 --> 22:04.991
- Yeah.
[laughter]

22:05.032 --> 22:06.332
- Hi.
- Mm.

22:06.367 --> 22:07.577
- Have you seen John?

22:07.618 --> 22:09.698
I’m meeting him for a drink.
- Nope.

22:09.745 --> 22:12.405
- Oh, why don’t you sit with us
until he gets here?

22:12.456 --> 22:13.576
- Yeah.
- We’re celebrating.

22:13.624 --> 22:15.084
We just got a temporary
restraining order

22:15.125 --> 22:16.285
for the resort.

22:16.335 --> 22:17.585
- Oh, that’s great.

22:17.628 --> 22:19.958
Whoo-hoo.
- Okay.

22:20.005 --> 22:22.255
I thought you’d be a little bit
more excited than that.

22:22.299 --> 22:24.679
- Oh, I am. I’m sorry.

22:24.718 --> 22:26.798
I’ve been waiting to hear
from a friend of mine.

22:26.846 --> 22:29.386
They’re in trouble,
so until I hear back,

22:29.431 --> 22:31.561
I’m just a little worried
about them, you know?

22:31.600 --> 22:33.730
- Yeah. That’s hard.

22:33.769 --> 22:36.479
- I just don’t like this
feeling of being helpless.

22:36.522 --> 22:39.022
- You’re, like, the least
helpless person I know.

22:39.066 --> 22:40.276
Look at us.

22:40.317 --> 22:41.607
We’re slowing down
this huge resort company.

22:41.652 --> 22:43.452
There’s always something
that can be done.

22:43.487 --> 22:46.277
- Thanks. Thanks.

22:46.323 --> 22:48.453
- Hey, I get the feeling
helpless thing.

22:48.492 --> 22:50.242
That’s me too these days.

22:50.286 --> 22:52.616
Ben’s--he’s going through
something.

22:52.663 --> 22:54.293
He’s been having
these nightmares.

22:54.331 --> 22:55.791
He’s even been sleepwalking.

22:55.833 --> 22:58.543
- Sleepwalking.
He’s doing that again?

22:59.587 --> 23:01.667
- You know about that?
- Oh, yeah.

23:01.714 --> 23:04.224
When we were young,
he wrote a paper on it

23:04.258 --> 23:05.878
for English class.

23:05.926 --> 23:09.466
Apparently, he ended up outside
and got locked out,

23:09.513 --> 23:12.393
and they found him
on the porch the next morning

23:12.433 --> 23:13.643
snuggling up
to the neighbor’s cat.

23:13.684 --> 23:15.234
- Oh, that’s awful.

23:15.269 --> 23:17.439
- I--I had no idea.

23:17.479 --> 23:19.019
Poor Ben.
- Yeah.

23:20.649 --> 23:23.989
My cat was never the same,
either.

23:24.028 --> 23:25.858
- Oh.

23:25.905 --> 23:29.325
- [indistinct].
I’m clear. How about you?

23:29.366 --> 23:31.576
- All clear.
- [indistinct].

23:31.619 --> 23:33.329
- [indistinct].

23:33.370 --> 23:34.660
You two cover the door
at the perimeter.

23:34.705 --> 23:35.795
- Augh.

23:35.831 --> 23:36.921
- He’ll have to come
through us.

23:36.957 --> 23:38.167
- Let’s go. Let’s do it.

23:38.208 --> 23:40.038
[indistinct shouting]

23:40.085 --> 23:41.915
- [grunts]

23:41.962 --> 23:45.632
[eerie music]

23:45.674 --> 23:47.934
I remember you assholes.

23:47.968 --> 23:49.088
[alarm blaring]

23:49.136 --> 23:50.346
[energy blasts]

23:50.387 --> 23:51.927
all: Ahh!

23:51.972 --> 23:54.022
[tense music]

23:54.058 --> 23:56.058
- Why kill soldiers
who attack you

23:56.101 --> 23:58.651
when they may be useful
to you in the future?

23:58.687 --> 24:00.057
It is like buying pizza

24:00.105 --> 24:02.515
and shoving extra napkins
into your pocket.

24:02.566 --> 24:05.066
You never know
when they may come in handy.

24:05.110 --> 24:08.410
♪ ♪

24:08.447 --> 24:10.027
[chuckles]

24:10.074 --> 24:11.834
[alarm blaring]

24:11.867 --> 24:14.447
Hey, dickhead!

24:14.495 --> 24:16.415
[laughs]
- Straight ahead!

24:16.455 --> 24:19.705
- There he is, right there!

24:19.750 --> 24:21.210
Hold up.
- Hold, hold.

24:21.251 --> 24:22.541
- Holy shit.

24:22.586 --> 24:24.336
Schneider, Bennewitz,
you’re up.

24:24.380 --> 24:28.510
[all grunting, shouting]

24:28.550 --> 24:30.590
♪ ♪

24:30.636 --> 24:32.886
- Come on!
- Okay.

24:32.930 --> 24:35.930
- You are making
a huge mistake.

24:35.975 --> 24:37.735
[rapid gunfire]

24:37.768 --> 24:41.978
You have no idea what these
things are capable of.

24:42.022 --> 24:44.902
Any one of them
could be an alien.

24:44.942 --> 24:46.862
[alarm blaring]

24:46.902 --> 24:48.112
- An alien.

24:48.153 --> 24:49.863
- Hey!

24:49.905 --> 24:51.985
You are
that high-haired gentleman

24:52.032 --> 24:55.082
that I met
at the alien convention.

24:55.119 --> 24:58.159
I ate your...
flower-shaped fruit.

24:58.205 --> 25:00.365
- That was you?
- [laughs]

25:00.416 --> 25:02.076
- I have so many questions
for you.

25:02.126 --> 25:03.746
Where are you from?

25:03.794 --> 25:05.594
Who were your first teachers?

25:05.629 --> 25:06.879
And when...
[loud clattering]

25:06.922 --> 25:09.512
- Get down!
- Hey, I--

25:09.550 --> 25:11.470
I’m a little bit busy
right now.

25:11.510 --> 25:14.260
Uh, maybe we could do this
another time.

25:14.304 --> 25:17.144
- Sure.
Thanks for springing me.

25:17.182 --> 25:18.142
Oh.

25:18.183 --> 25:21.143
[gentle music]

25:21.186 --> 25:22.476
♪ ♪

25:22.521 --> 25:24.941
- I’m not really a hugger.

25:24.982 --> 25:26.482
You should run.

25:27.943 --> 25:29.193
- Exit?

25:29.236 --> 25:30.946
- Oh, it’s down the hallway.

25:30.988 --> 25:33.488
Take a left just after
the dead bodies.

25:33.532 --> 25:35.162
- Thanks.

25:35.200 --> 25:37.160
I knew they existed!

25:37.202 --> 25:38.202
- This way.

25:43.584 --> 25:44.793
[alarm blaring]

25:44.793 --> 25:47.087
- [shouting indistinctly]

25:47.087 --> 25:50.757
- [warbling]

25:52.593 --> 25:56.103
- [grunts]

25:56.138 --> 25:58.388
- [warbling]

25:58.432 --> 26:01.482
- There you are.

26:01.518 --> 26:03.348
[warbles]

26:03.395 --> 26:06.355
- [warbles]

26:06.398 --> 26:07.648
[squeaks]

26:07.691 --> 26:10.401
[high-pitched tone]

26:10.444 --> 26:13.034
- Hello, Harry. I’m Goliath.

26:13.072 --> 26:15.282
[alarm blaring]

26:15.324 --> 26:17.664
[tense music]

26:17.701 --> 26:19.121
[computer beeps]

26:19.161 --> 26:21.711
- Do you have any idea
how dangerous

26:21.747 --> 26:23.457
those specimens could be?

26:23.499 --> 26:25.129
- I don’t need your warnings.

26:25.167 --> 26:27.667
I’m an expert in all of this.
- [sighs]

26:27.711 --> 26:29.801
- They don’t call me
the Alien Tracker for nothing.

26:29.838 --> 26:34.008
- How many aliens have you
actually tracked and captured?

26:34.051 --> 26:36.091
Besides the one
that you’re working with.

26:36.136 --> 26:37.506
- Why besides the one?

26:37.554 --> 26:38.764
Isn’t one enough?
It’s an alien.

26:38.806 --> 26:41.266
- Anyone can find
just one alien.

26:41.308 --> 26:44.438
- No. Not anyone.

26:44.478 --> 26:46.518
Do you have an alien?

26:46.563 --> 26:47.943
- I’m not saying.

26:47.981 --> 26:49.771
- That’s a no.
- Fine.

26:49.817 --> 26:51.607
- You don’t have one, and I do.

26:51.652 --> 26:53.072
- Okay.
- Good.

26:53.112 --> 26:55.612
I’m glad we agree.

26:55.656 --> 26:57.696
Do you really have an alien?

26:57.741 --> 26:59.161
[high-pitched tone]

27:00.577 --> 27:02.157
- Finally.

27:02.204 --> 27:05.214
I have gotten what I have been
searching for,

27:05.249 --> 27:09.459
the message I traveled back
in time to give to myself.

27:09.503 --> 27:10.803
[sighs]

27:10.838 --> 27:13.338
Thank you for your service.

27:13.382 --> 27:15.182
I do not need you anymore.

27:15.217 --> 27:18.677
You can go and find
some goats to eat.

27:18.720 --> 27:21.180
- [warbling]

27:21.223 --> 27:23.353
Daddy.

27:23.392 --> 27:25.892
[gentle music]

27:25.936 --> 27:27.146
Daddy.

27:27.187 --> 27:29.107
- [sighs]

27:29.148 --> 27:30.978
What am I feeling?

27:31.024 --> 27:33.494
Is this the connection
between a parent and child

27:33.527 --> 27:35.197
humans talk about?

27:35.237 --> 27:38.317
Connection is supposed
to make you feel stronger,

27:38.365 --> 27:41.785
so why do I feel weaker?

27:41.827 --> 27:44.077
I need to hold you.

27:44.121 --> 27:45.251
- [squeaks]

27:45.289 --> 27:48.209
♪ ♪

27:48.250 --> 27:50.460
- I am...your father.

27:50.502 --> 27:52.382
[Neil Diamond’s "Heartlight"]

27:52.421 --> 27:55.671
And you are my...

27:55.716 --> 27:58.216
spawn.
[chuckles]

27:58.260 --> 27:59.550
I will protect you.

27:59.595 --> 28:01.605
- ♪ Just made a friend ♪

28:01.638 --> 28:06.428
♪ ♪

28:06.476 --> 28:09.226
♪ A friend is someone
you need ♪

28:09.271 --> 28:11.611
- Come here, you little shit.

28:11.648 --> 28:12.768
What?

28:12.816 --> 28:14.276
I got your nose.

28:14.318 --> 28:16.188
I got your nose.
- [screams]

28:16.236 --> 28:17.276
- [laughs]

28:17.321 --> 28:18.531
I don’t actually have it.

28:18.572 --> 28:19.992
Don’t freak out.

28:20.032 --> 28:23.122
Peek-a-baah!

28:23.160 --> 28:25.540
I’ll eat your heart out!

28:25.579 --> 28:27.249
♪ ♪

28:27.289 --> 28:28.669
Whee-oo!

28:28.707 --> 28:30.207
- ♪ Turn on your heartlight ♪

28:30.250 --> 28:31.630
- Whee--oh, God.

28:31.668 --> 28:33.458
Oh, sweet Jesus.

28:33.503 --> 28:35.843
- ♪ Wherever you go ♪

28:35.881 --> 28:38.971
♪ Let it make a happy glow ♪

28:39.009 --> 28:42.259
♪ For all the world to see ♪

28:42.304 --> 28:44.644
♪ ♪

28:44.681 --> 28:47.811
♪ Turn on your heartlight ♪

28:47.851 --> 28:52.231
♪ In the middle
of a young boy’s dream ♪

28:52.272 --> 28:55.112
♪ Don’t wake me up too soon ♪

28:55.150 --> 28:59.860
♪ ♪

28:59.905 --> 29:03.245
♪ Gonna take a ride
across the Moon ♪

29:03.283 --> 29:06.543
[Werepig growling]

29:06.578 --> 29:08.998
- Oh, yeah! Suck it, Werepig!

29:09.039 --> 29:09.999
[laughter]

29:10.040 --> 29:11.290
- And with only
a Tentacle Spike.

29:11.333 --> 29:14.093
- Nice.
- Yeah. That’s my best friend.

29:14.127 --> 29:16.337
- Maybe it’s time
to take a break.

29:16.380 --> 29:18.670
- You’re right.
We need more drinks.

29:18.715 --> 29:20.425
- Ooh, ooh. Get me a soda.
- Two sodas.

29:20.467 --> 29:24.007
- These spicy chips are, like,
burning a hole in my stomach.

29:24.054 --> 29:26.014
- Oof.

29:26.056 --> 29:29.306
[sighs]

29:29.351 --> 29:33.271
- Elliot’s a jerk
for breaking up with you.

29:33.313 --> 29:34.733
- Aww, thanks, Jude.

29:34.773 --> 29:36.323
- Yeah.

29:36.358 --> 29:39.108
You’re probably, like,
really worried now.

29:39.152 --> 29:43.202
He’s probably just, like,
banging chicks left and right.

29:43.240 --> 29:45.780
- Well, now I am.

29:45.826 --> 29:48.286
- What do you think
you’re doing, Dad?

29:48.328 --> 29:50.748
- Isn’t it obvious?

29:50.789 --> 29:53.879
- I’m helping D’arcy
find Glommer’s Statue.

29:53.917 --> 29:55.457
- Okay, you promised
to talk to D’arcy.

29:55.502 --> 29:57.462
What happened to that?

29:57.504 --> 29:59.924
- Well, she seemed a little raw

29:59.965 --> 30:02.185
when she came back
from her meeting.

30:02.217 --> 30:04.967
Didn’t seem the right time
to push her out into the world.

30:05.012 --> 30:06.762
- Oh, God.
[chuckles]

30:06.805 --> 30:09.765
Dad, I love how compassionate
you are.

30:09.808 --> 30:11.638
And I get it. Really, I do.

30:11.685 --> 30:13.775
I was the one rubbing her feet
and holding her head up

30:13.812 --> 30:15.652
while she was throwing up
detoxing, okay?

30:15.689 --> 30:17.819
But we can’t--

30:17.858 --> 30:19.818
we can’t keep indulging her.

30:19.860 --> 30:21.860
She’s not a child.

30:21.903 --> 30:23.613
If you don’t push her
into the real world

30:23.655 --> 30:26.485
and force her to live her life,
you’re just enabling her.

30:26.533 --> 30:28.123
- You’re absolutely right.

30:28.160 --> 30:29.660
- I know.

30:29.703 --> 30:31.003
It’s time she moves out.

30:31.038 --> 30:32.618
- It’s time for you
to move out.

30:32.664 --> 30:33.924
- What was that?

30:33.957 --> 30:36.167
- You’re right.
You’re not a child.

30:36.209 --> 30:38.919
I love you too much
to enable you.

30:38.962 --> 30:40.842
Consider this your push.

30:40.881 --> 30:43.631
[gentle piano music]

30:43.675 --> 30:45.335
- Yeah, but--

30:45.385 --> 30:46.795
that’s not...

30:46.845 --> 30:48.885
♪ ♪

30:48.930 --> 30:52.270
[alarm blaring]

30:52.309 --> 30:53.689
- Come on. Come on.
- Come on.

30:53.727 --> 30:57.437
-I’m right behind you.

30:57.481 --> 31:00.361
[tense music]

31:00.400 --> 31:07.370
♪ ♪

31:12.704 --> 31:16.544
- Oh, my God.

31:16.583 --> 31:18.133
It’s my son.

31:18.168 --> 31:20.248
- What?
- My son is here.

31:21.254 --> 31:22.964
You’ve had him this whole time.

31:23.006 --> 31:24.756
[computer beeps]

31:25.759 --> 31:27.549
- Uncuff me.

31:27.594 --> 31:29.764
I can help you.

31:29.805 --> 31:31.475
- Forgive me if I don’t
believe you.

31:31.515 --> 31:34.435
[tense music]

31:40.899 --> 31:43.569
[gentle acoustic guitar music]

31:43.610 --> 31:46.610
- [sighs]

31:46.655 --> 31:52.745
♪ ♪

31:52.786 --> 31:54.656
- [grunts]
’Scuse me. Excuse me.

31:54.704 --> 31:55.834
- Okay.
- If I could just tell you

31:55.872 --> 31:57.752
about your car’s extended
warranty.

31:57.791 --> 31:59.171
- [laughs]
- Excuse me.

31:59.209 --> 32:00.209
Excuse me.

32:00.252 --> 32:01.502
- Ugh.

32:01.545 --> 32:04.055
[laughs]

32:04.089 --> 32:05.759
Oh.

32:05.799 --> 32:07.339
Remember when we used
to lay here

32:07.384 --> 32:09.934
and stare at these stars
when we were little kids?

32:09.970 --> 32:11.760
- [chuckles]
And high teenagers.

32:11.805 --> 32:14.275
- [laughs] Oh, yeah. That too.

32:14.307 --> 32:16.057
[laughs]

32:16.101 --> 32:18.691
- And we would talk for hours
about our future.

32:18.728 --> 32:19.898
- Mm.

32:19.938 --> 32:22.358
- We were both gonna marry
Lee Smith.

32:22.399 --> 32:25.489
- [laughs]
- You know, and then I’d...

32:25.527 --> 32:28.357
screw it up inevitably and you
could have him to yourself.

32:28.405 --> 32:30.705
- Hey, you were under
a lot of pressure

32:30.740 --> 32:33.700
being in that tournament.

32:33.743 --> 32:35.873
- Yeah, don’t make excuses
for me.

32:35.912 --> 32:38.042
You know, other people were
in the tournament.

32:38.081 --> 32:39.621
They didn’t get hooked on pills
and have to hole up

32:39.666 --> 32:41.496
at their best friend’s house
because being alone

32:41.543 --> 32:43.593
is worse than death.

32:43.628 --> 32:47.718
- You’re not alone.
- [sighs]

32:47.757 --> 32:49.127
I know.

32:49.176 --> 32:52.506
It’s stupid. I’m an adult.

32:52.554 --> 32:54.894
I should be able
to take care of my own shit.

32:54.931 --> 32:57.391
- [scoffs] It’s not stupid.

32:57.434 --> 33:00.064
I’m clearly not a fan
of being alone either.

33:00.103 --> 33:03.733
I mean,
I haven’t lived on my own in...

33:03.773 --> 33:05.573
well, ever.

33:05.609 --> 33:06.729
[sighs]

33:06.776 --> 33:09.276
I’ve never even had
my own place.

33:09.321 --> 33:11.911
- Maybe we could
move in together.

33:11.948 --> 33:14.238
Then you’d have your own place.

33:14.284 --> 33:15.414
- Really?

33:15.452 --> 33:17.412
Oh, my God.

33:17.454 --> 33:20.254
Ooh, maybe we could get
a house by a lake.

33:20.290 --> 33:22.710
Oh, like your grandmother’s
old cabin.

33:22.751 --> 33:24.211
- Oh, my God.

33:24.252 --> 33:26.592
We’d have to get one of those
old TVs like she had.

33:26.630 --> 33:28.800
- Yeah, with the rabbit ears.

33:28.840 --> 33:31.220
[laughs]
- Yeah.

33:31.259 --> 33:33.759
That thing was fuzzy as shit.
- Mm-hmm.

33:33.803 --> 33:36.013
- You couldn’t see anything.

33:36.056 --> 33:38.266
And so Gramps would hold
the antenna...

33:38.308 --> 33:40.268
- Mm-hmm.

33:40.310 --> 33:42.400
- So her soaps would come
into focus

33:42.437 --> 33:43.937
and she could watch.

33:43.980 --> 33:46.020
- God. He loved her so much.

33:46.066 --> 33:47.356
That was so cute.

33:47.400 --> 33:49.740
♪ ♪

33:49.778 --> 33:52.318
- I...

33:52.364 --> 33:54.454
I get that--that--

33:54.491 --> 33:55.781
that fuzziness.

33:55.825 --> 33:57.985
It’s...

33:58.036 --> 34:00.286
it’s like my life
in a nutshell.

34:00.330 --> 34:03.420
♪ ♪

34:03.458 --> 34:05.628
That’s why I had to be here
this week.

34:05.669 --> 34:07.799
♪ ♪

34:07.837 --> 34:11.587
When I’m around you,
it’s like...

34:11.633 --> 34:15.143
you’re holding the antenna.

34:15.178 --> 34:18.308
Everything gets clearer.

34:18.348 --> 34:20.388
- I’ll always hold
your antenna.

34:20.433 --> 34:21.853
♪ ♪

34:21.893 --> 34:23.643
- Gross.
- [laughs]

34:23.687 --> 34:25.227
[phone buzzing]

34:25.272 --> 34:26.772
’Scuse me.
- Oh!

34:26.815 --> 34:28.365
[laughter]

34:28.400 --> 34:29.940
- Hello? [laughs]

34:29.985 --> 34:32.905
♪ ♪

34:32.946 --> 34:36.066
What?

34:36.116 --> 34:38.986
Oh, okay. Whoa.

34:39.035 --> 34:42.455
Thanks, Ellen.

34:42.497 --> 34:43.997
- What is it?

34:44.040 --> 34:45.790
- It’s Ben.

34:45.834 --> 34:49.924
[all grunting]

34:49.963 --> 34:51.513
- I’m looking for my son!

34:51.548 --> 34:54.508
[tense music]

34:54.551 --> 34:55.891
♪ ♪

34:55.927 --> 34:57.797
I’m looking for my son!

34:57.846 --> 35:01.426
♪ ♪

35:01.474 --> 35:02.524
- Dad?

35:02.559 --> 35:04.519
[all grunting]

35:04.561 --> 35:05.691
- Son!

35:05.729 --> 35:09.439
♪ ♪

35:09.482 --> 35:12.692
- Robert. Stop.

35:12.736 --> 35:14.106
Don’t go to him.

35:14.154 --> 35:16.034
You belong to us.

35:16.072 --> 35:22.952
♪ ♪

35:22.996 --> 35:24.656
You made the wrong choice.

35:27.876 --> 35:29.456
- No!

35:29.502 --> 35:30.882
[gunshot]

35:30.920 --> 35:37.010
♪ ♪

35:37.052 --> 35:38.552
[dramatic music]

35:38.595 --> 35:40.895
[both grunting]

35:40.930 --> 35:42.060
- [snarls]

35:42.098 --> 35:45.888
- [gagging]

35:45.935 --> 35:47.015
- [growls]
- [warbles]

35:47.062 --> 35:49.062
- [growls]

35:49.105 --> 35:53.025
[grunting]

35:53.068 --> 35:54.778
- Get him. Get him.

35:54.819 --> 35:56.899
Get him.

35:56.946 --> 35:58.566
- Ahh! Ugh!

35:58.615 --> 36:01.495
[tense music]

36:01.534 --> 36:06.254
♪ ♪

36:06.289 --> 36:08.919
- You f--you found your baby.

36:08.958 --> 36:10.998
♪ ♪

36:11.044 --> 36:12.554
- So did you.

36:14.214 --> 36:15.884
- It’s too late for me.

36:15.924 --> 36:18.764
♪ ♪

36:18.802 --> 36:20.012
♪ ♪

36:20.053 --> 36:22.013
Please...

36:22.055 --> 36:23.225
save him.

36:25.475 --> 36:27.105
Save my son.

36:27.143 --> 36:34.283
♪ ♪

36:36.361 --> 36:40.781
[gasps]

36:40.824 --> 36:43.624
- Ahh! Robert!

36:43.660 --> 36:44.790
- Let’s go.

36:44.828 --> 36:49.958
♪ ♪

36:49.999 --> 36:52.919
[tense music]

36:52.961 --> 36:58.471
♪ ♪

36:58.508 --> 37:01.088
- [grunting]

37:01.136 --> 37:02.636
♪ ♪

37:02.679 --> 37:06.889
- Heh-heh-heh-heh.

37:06.933 --> 37:08.433
- Stop. Don’t move.

37:09.686 --> 37:11.976
- [growls]

37:12.021 --> 37:14.151
- You can’t take him.

37:14.190 --> 37:15.980
Put him down.

37:16.025 --> 37:17.565
- [screeches]

37:17.610 --> 37:21.070
♪ ♪

37:21.114 --> 37:22.664
[grunts]

37:22.699 --> 37:24.159
[gasps]

37:24.200 --> 37:29.660
♪ ♪

37:29.706 --> 37:31.326
- [growling]

37:31.374 --> 37:33.004
- [gasps]

37:33.042 --> 37:34.502
- [squeaks]

37:36.629 --> 37:38.009
- [whimpers]

37:38.047 --> 37:43.927
♪ ♪

37:43.970 --> 37:46.930
[panting]

37:46.973 --> 37:49.063
- We’re in here!
- [indistinct].

37:49.100 --> 37:54.150
- This way.

37:54.189 --> 37:56.399
- [panting]

37:56.441 --> 37:57.361
[sighs]

38:00.904 --> 38:02.614
- Look, I’m fine.

38:02.655 --> 38:03.485
- Don’t worry.

38:03.531 --> 38:04.871
Just go along with my story.

38:04.908 --> 38:06.828
I already told the cops
you hit an ice patch.

38:06.868 --> 38:08.038
You weren’t drinking.

38:08.077 --> 38:09.367
- I--I wasn’t drinking.

38:09.412 --> 38:11.122
- Exactly. Just like that.

38:13.082 --> 38:14.252
- Oh, my God.

38:14.292 --> 38:15.582
What happened?

38:15.627 --> 38:16.837
- He’s fine.
He veered off the road.

38:16.878 --> 38:17.998
He definitely wasn’t drunk.

38:18.046 --> 38:20.336
- I wasn’t.
- That’s what I said.

38:21.424 --> 38:23.474
- Thank God you’re okay.

38:23.510 --> 38:25.300
- I’ll let you two be alone.

38:25.345 --> 38:27.685
But just know,
if you decide to have sex,

38:27.722 --> 38:29.682
these walls have ears.

38:29.724 --> 38:31.234
Mostly because I stand close by
and listen,

38:31.267 --> 38:32.727
and my phone camera’s set
to 4K.

38:36.272 --> 38:37.572
- I--I wasn’t drunk.

38:37.607 --> 38:41.187
I nodded off for a second,
but I’m fine, really.

38:41.236 --> 38:42.396
- We have to do something
about this.

38:42.445 --> 38:43.895
We cannot live this way.

38:43.947 --> 38:45.567
- I was just a little tired.

38:45.615 --> 38:48.745
- Yes, because
you haven’t been sleeping.

38:48.785 --> 38:52.295
I think I know why.

38:52.330 --> 38:54.170
Liv told me the story

38:54.207 --> 38:57.337
about you getting locked out
of your house.

38:57.377 --> 39:00.377
And that and the dreams
that you’ve been having

39:00.421 --> 39:02.971
about your family
not helping you.

39:03.007 --> 39:04.547
They mean something.

39:04.592 --> 39:06.012
You felt abandoned by them,

39:06.052 --> 39:07.432
and now you feel
abandoned by me,

39:07.470 --> 39:09.390
because I’ve been fighting you
so hard on the resort,

39:09.430 --> 39:11.390
but you don’t have to worry
about that anymore, okay?

39:11.432 --> 39:13.102
There’s--there’s a lot of good
that can come

39:13.142 --> 39:14.272
from having a resort in town.

39:14.310 --> 39:16.480
So I’m with you.

39:16.521 --> 39:18.691
- I don’t want you to stop
doing what you believe in.

39:20.316 --> 39:22.146
- I have to do something.

39:22.193 --> 39:25.243
- You know how they say
your life...

39:25.280 --> 39:27.950
flashes before your eyes when
you think you’re gonna die?

39:27.991 --> 39:29.911
[gentle music]

39:29.951 --> 39:33.701
I feel like that might have
happened to me.

39:33.746 --> 39:34.786
- Oh, honey.

39:34.831 --> 39:35.921
- I--I don’t know.

39:35.957 --> 39:38.247
It was, like, all of a sudden,

39:38.293 --> 39:42.133
when I was crashing, I...

39:42.171 --> 39:45.131
remembered all these things
at once.

39:46.342 --> 39:49.472
You know,
all these special moments.

39:50.555 --> 39:52.815
And they were all here.

39:52.849 --> 39:55.479
You know, in Patience.

39:55.518 --> 39:57.808
With people that I love.

39:57.854 --> 40:00.694
With you...and Max.

40:02.483 --> 40:04.743
Asta, Dan, D’arcy,

40:04.777 --> 40:07.147
Kayla, Liv, Mike.

40:07.196 --> 40:08.566
- [coughs]

40:08.615 --> 40:10.785
Ellen.

40:10.825 --> 40:12.735
- Ellen.
- Aww.

40:12.785 --> 40:15.575
♪ ♪

40:15.622 --> 40:22.342
- I’ve been trying so hard
to change this town...

40:22.378 --> 40:25.708
to make it perfect.

40:25.757 --> 40:27.217
And it already is.

40:28.426 --> 40:29.836
At least to me.

40:29.886 --> 40:31.966
And...

40:32.013 --> 40:33.723
I don’t want it to change.

40:33.765 --> 40:35.815
♪ ♪

40:35.850 --> 40:37.770
I’m just so tired...

40:37.810 --> 40:39.980
of trying to get everyone
to like me.

40:41.439 --> 40:44.069
- Oh, honey.

40:44.108 --> 40:46.528
Everybody loves you.

40:46.569 --> 40:48.199
- [sighs]

40:48.237 --> 40:51.487
No, they don’t.

40:51.532 --> 40:53.662
I’m just the mayor to them.

40:53.701 --> 40:58.081
- No.
- But I know that you do.

40:58.122 --> 41:00.712
You know,
and that’s what matters.

41:00.750 --> 41:03.170
- I do.

41:03.211 --> 41:09.881
♪ ♪

41:09.926 --> 41:12.886
[tense music]

41:12.929 --> 41:15.389
♪ ♪

41:15.431 --> 41:18.061
- There you are.

41:18.101 --> 41:21.231
But who is that with you?

41:21.270 --> 41:23.900
[dramatic music]

41:23.940 --> 41:29.070
[engine revving]

41:29.112 --> 41:30.322
[gate clangs]

41:30.363 --> 41:35.493
♪ ♪

41:35.535 --> 41:37.045
[alarm blaring]

41:37.078 --> 41:38.408
- Secure the room.
- All right, got it.

41:38.454 --> 41:41.334
[tense music]

41:41.374 --> 41:43.334
Clear.

41:43.376 --> 41:46.916
- Thank God I still have the
alien ball.

41:46.963 --> 41:48.713
Oh, shit.

41:48.756 --> 41:51.756
[The Felice Brothers’
"Radio Song"]

41:51.801 --> 41:57.931
♪ ♪

41:57.974 --> 41:59.604
- The Alien Tracker
was committed

41:59.642 --> 42:01.602
to finding his child.

42:01.644 --> 42:03.104
But it wasn’t just commitment

42:03.146 --> 42:05.146
that made him willing
to die for it.

42:05.189 --> 42:07.439
- [babbles]

42:07.483 --> 42:09.403
[retches]

42:09.444 --> 42:10.904
The alien ball.

42:10.945 --> 42:14.065
♪ ♪

42:14.115 --> 42:17.955
[laughs]

42:17.994 --> 42:20.294
There was love too.

42:20.329 --> 42:22.709
- ♪ Anna Bell ♪

42:22.749 --> 42:25.959
♪ The dying leaves ♪

42:26.002 --> 42:30.462
♪ Are dancing off
of the trees ♪

42:30.506 --> 42:32.756
♪ They got an easy way ♪

42:32.800 --> 42:34.970
- The word "commitment"
becomes something different

42:35.011 --> 42:36.641
when you add love to it.

42:36.679 --> 42:38.639
- ♪ Let’s you and me ♪

42:38.681 --> 42:41.931
♪ Go dancing too ♪

42:41.976 --> 42:44.266
♪ Wreck our dancing shoes ♪

42:44.312 --> 42:46.732
- Humans call it devotion.

42:46.773 --> 42:48.323
- ♪ Hey, hey, hey ♪

42:48.357 --> 42:51.777
♪ ♪

42:51.819 --> 42:55.319
♪ Anna Bell, the dying stars ♪

42:55.364 --> 42:56.914
- What’d she say?
Are there any details?

42:56.949 --> 42:59.909
- No, just that Ben was
in a car accident.

42:59.952 --> 43:03.002
- This feeling of devotion
is not just for families.

43:03.039 --> 43:06.169
If there is enough love,
anybody will feel it.

43:06.209 --> 43:07.419
♪ ♪

43:07.460 --> 43:10.000
- ♪ Let’s you and me ♪

43:10.046 --> 43:11.376
♪ Go falling too ♪

43:11.422 --> 43:13.592
- I was surprised
by the feeling of love I had

43:13.633 --> 43:15.803
when I saw the baby.

43:15.843 --> 43:18.353
That is understandable,
because I am new to Earth.

43:18.387 --> 43:20.307
- ♪ Hey, hey, hey ♪

43:20.348 --> 43:23.478
♪ ♪

43:23.518 --> 43:26.348
♪ Please, don’t you ever die ♪

43:26.395 --> 43:29.145
♪ You ever die, you ever die ♪

43:29.190 --> 43:31.860
- But why does love surprise
humans?

43:31.901 --> 43:34.031
- ♪ You moved me
all of my life ♪

43:34.070 --> 43:37.660
- I hope he’s okay.

43:37.698 --> 43:40.238
- Love is like air.

43:40.284 --> 43:42.294
Even if you cannot see it,

43:42.328 --> 43:44.198
you have to know it is there.

43:44.247 --> 43:45.867
- ♪ Radio song ♪

43:45.915 --> 43:49.595
♪ After every radio’s gone ♪

43:49.627 --> 43:51.627
♪ Radio’s gone ♪

43:51.671 --> 43:56.931
♪ Radio’s gone ♪

43:56.968 --> 44:03.848
♪ ♪
